---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Projects">
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="eyebrow">Projects</div>
    <h1>Product work, memory systems, and the runtime layer under AI collaboration.</h1>
    <p class="hero-lede">
      These are the threads I keep returning to. Some are product surfaces, some are internal systems,
      and some are infrastructure that only becomes visible when it fails.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">Primary threads</span>

    <div class="project" id="sleephub">
      <h3>SleepHub</h3>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">product</span>
        <span class="tag">ambient AI</span>
        <span class="tag">voice agents</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Bedside AI system for autonomous sleep coaching and monitoring at
        <a href="https://asleep.ai">Asleep</a>. It combines contactless sensing, voice interaction,
        and personalized health insight delivery into something that has to work quietly in the background.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the anchor project: real product work where applied AI, runtime behavior,
        and ambient interface design all collide.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="project" id="knowledge-os">
      <h3>Knowledge OS</h3>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">personal OS</span>
        <span class="tag">markdown-first</span>
        <span class="tag">agent memory</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        A private, agent-native personal operating system built around explicit files.
        Raw sources flow into compiled pages for topics, projects, people, and decisions.
        This public site is one curated output of that system.
      </p>
      <p>
        The pattern matters more than the brand: private memory upstream, durable public expression downstream.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="project" id="agent-infra">
      <h3>Agent Infrastructure</h3>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">runtime</span>
        <span class="tag">agent control</span>
        <span class="tag">harness engineering</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Tooling and patterns for making agents reliable enough for real workflows.
        Focus areas include session lifecycle, context packaging, structured control,
        memory continuity, and the interface bridges that make strong systems usable.
      </p>
      <p>
        The interesting problems are usually not model capability problems. They are runtime problems.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">Utilities and experiments</span>
    <div class="project" id="utilities">
      <h3>Utilities and experiments</h3>
      <p>
        Smaller tools that remove workflow friction: CLI adapters, automation glue, environment management,
        and the little systems that make bigger systems livable.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
